		  the one-imensional velocity dispersion, f is the growth
		  rate, and b_{pk}(k) and b_{vel}(k) are k-ependent linear
		  spatial and velocity bias factors. For peaks, the value of
		  s_{vel} depends upon the functional form of b_{vel}. The
		  peaks model is remarkable because it has unbiased
		  velocities - peak motions are driven by dark matter flows -
		  but, in order to achieve this, b_{vel} is k-ependent. We
		  speculate that this is true in general: k-ependence of the
		  spatial bias will lead to k-ependence of b_{vel} even if
		  the biased tracers flow with the dark matter. Because of
		  the k-ependence of the linear bias parameters, standard
		  manipulations applied to the peak model will lead to
		  k-ependent estimates of the growth factor that could
		  erroneously be interpreted as a signature of modified dark
		  energy or gravity. We use the Fisher formalism to show that
		  the constraint on the growth rate f is degraded by a factor
